{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17636008","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17636008"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:22:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:22:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17550"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17550","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17550"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.72,0.08,0.16,0,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10240"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72421"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10240","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10240"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17550"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57891"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"2560"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"6114"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23946"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23947"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72421","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72421"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe common peroneal nerve passes around the neck of the fibula where it is vulnerable to compression.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following movements is most likely to be affected by common peroneal nerve injury?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ankle dorsiflexion","Ankle inversion","Ankle plantar flexion","Knee extension","Knee flexion"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe common peroneal nerve innervates the muscles responsible for \u003Cstrong\u003Eankle dorsiflexion\u003C/strong\u003E, which is the most significantly affected movement in peroneal nerve palsy. This results in foot drop, where patients have difficulty lifting their foot while walking.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnkle inversion\u003C/strong\u003E is controlled by the tibial nerve via the tibialis posterior muscle\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnkle plantar flexion\u003C/strong\u003E is controlled by the tibial nerve via the gastrocnemius and soleus muscles\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EKnee extension\u003C/strong\u003E is controlled by the femoral nerve via the quadriceps muscles\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EKnee flexion\u003C/strong\u003E is controlled by the sciatic nerve via the hamstring muscles\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe common peroneal nerve supplies the anterior and lateral compartments of the leg, containing muscles that dorsiflex and evert the ankle. When injured, patients typically present with foot drop and sensory changes over the dorsum of the foot.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The common peroneal nerve innervates muscles responsible for ankle dorsiflexion and eversion.","Injury to the common peroneal nerve typically occurs at the fibular head where it is superficial.","Common peroneal nerve palsy presents with foot drop due to weakness of ankle dorsiflexion."],"references":["Fortier LM, Markel M, Thomas BG, Sherman WF, Thomas BH, Kaye AD. An Update on Peroneal Nerve Entrapment and Neuropathy. Orthop Rev (Pavia). 2021 Jun 19;13(2):24937. doi: 10.52965/001c.24937. PMID: 34745471; PMCID: PMC8567814.","Baima J, Krivickas L. Evaluation and 